This request seeks records relating to the Facebook page located at https://www.facebook.com/jointheboldest. An example of what each of these records look like is attached and available at https://bit.ly/facebookfoia.

In order to access the requested information, you will first need to take the following steps:

1. Log into the page account or a Facebook account with managerial access to the Facebook page. For information on this type of access, see: https://www.facebook.com/help/187316341316631.)
2. "Switch" to the page account. To do so, click your profile photo in the top right, then click "See all profiles", then select the Page you want to switch into. (See the instructions here: https://www.facebook.com/help/123930246348340).
3. Click "Professional dashboard" on the left, or go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/jointheboldest/?sk=professional_dashboard

I request the following information:

1. The "Page and Tagging" information. Once logged into the account, go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/settings/?tab=timeline&privacy_source=timeline_gear_menu.

2. The list of blocked users. This information is accessible by following these steps:
(a) Once logged into the account, go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/settings?tab=blocking
(b) Click "Edit" next to "Block users"
(c) Click "See your blocked list"

3. The list of blocked Pages. This information is accessible by following these steps:
(a) Once logged into the account, go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/settings?tab=blocking
(b) Click "Edit" next to "Block Pages"
(c) Click "See your blocked list"

4. The list of "Moderation Assist" criteria. This information is accessible by following either of these steps:
(a) Once logged into the account, go to the "Professional Dashboard" and then click "Moderation Assist" on the left side of the screen.
(b) Alternatively, visit this URL: https://www.facebook.com/jointheboldest/professional_dashboard/moderation_assist

5. If the "Moderation Assist" criteria includes "Comment has certain keywords", the list of keywords. This information is accessible by following the steps in (4) above, then:
(a) Click the pencil (edit) icon next to each of the criteria ("Comment has certain keywords").
(b) Click "Edit" from the drop-down menu.
(c) Click "Comment has certain keywords"
(d) On the right side of the "Keywords" menu, click the ellipsis menu ("...")
(e) Click "Copy list" from the dropdown menu.
(f) Provide the information from the list.

6. If the "Moderation Assist" criteria includes "Comment has specific links", the list of keywords. This information is accessible by following the steps in (4) above, then:
(a) Click the pencil (edit) icon next to each of the criteria ("Comment has specific links").
(b) Click "Edit" from the drop-down menu.
(c) Click "Comment has links to specific sites."
(d) Provide the information from the "Added sites" list.

7. The list of people with Facebook access. From the "Professional dashboard" page (https://www.facebook.com/jointheboldest/?sk=professional_dashboard), click "Page Access" on the left side of the screen. Alternatively, visit this URL: https://www.facebook.com/settings/?tab=profile_access

8. The list of moderation actions in the Activity log. This information is accessible by following these steps:
(a) Once logged into the account, go to the "Professional Dashboard."
(b) Click "Moderation Assist" on the left side of the screen (or go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/jointheboldest/professional_dashboard/moderation_assist).
(c) Click "Activity log" on the left side of the screen (or go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/jointheboldest/professional_dashboard/moderation_activity_log).
(c) From the dropdown menu labeled "Visible comments", select "Hidden comments".
(d) Continue scrolling down until the complete list is loaded.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Request: Photos of the President with cake (George W Bush (43) Presidential Library)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

This is a request under the Freedom of Information Act.  I hereby request the following records:

All photographs either taken by White House photographers or otherwise held by the Library which include or feature the president and a cake, birthday or otherwise.

I am journalist who writes extensively about FBI files - https://www.muckrock.com/project/subjects-matter-fbi-files-10/, which have received national and international attention - http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3219376/Undercover-FBI-agents-spy-annual-Burning-Man-festival-light-ongoing-war-terrorism-use-test-new-intelligence-collection-technology.html

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Sincerely,

JPat Brown

title: Gov. Ron DeSantis' Calendar

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Gov. Ron DeSantis' Calendar
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

The calendar of Gov. Ron DeSantis from Jan. 9, 2019 to present date. I request that the records be released in electronic format, preferably as an export from Microsoft Outlook or whatever similar software is used by the office.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Ben Welsh

communications.subject: RE: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Gov. Ron DeSantis' Calendar
communications.communication:
Good morning,

The Governor’s Office of Open Government is in receipt of your request for records as stated in your email below. If there is a fee associated with your request, you will be provided with a fee estimate for your review. Thank you for contacting the Executive Office of the Governor.

Sincerely,
Office of Open Government

communications.subject: RE: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Gov. Ron DeSantis' Calendar
communications.communication:
Good afternoon,



The Governor’s Office of Open Government has initiated a search for records responsive to your request, a copy of which is below.



Our initial search has found over 900 items potentially responsive to your request. An item identifies an email, attachment, meeting invitation, etc., and each item could result in multiple pages. All responsive pages require review for exempt and/or confidential information.



The Executive Office of the Governor is committed to public transparency and compliance with Florida’s Sunshine laws, and we will work to process your request as quickly as possible.  As you may know, complex or laborious requests that may require significant staff review or materials costs are subject to service charges.



Please let us know if you would like to limit the scope of your request.  Please note, if we do not hear from you within 30 days, our office will consider your request closed. Should that occur, you would be welcome to re-submit your request at any time.



Sincerely,

Open Government

title: Information regarding Tracey Collins and Eric Adams Communications.

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Information regarding Tracey Collins and Eric Adams Communications.
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am writing to request access to specific records related to Tracey Collins, Senior Youth Development Director for the New York City Department of Education, who has served as an elementary school principal. I am also requesting any communications related to Eric Adams, the current Mayor of New York City. I am requesting the following records under the Freedom of Information Law (FOIL):

All records related to Tracey Collins, including but not limited to:
Employment history with the New York City Department of Education
Performance evaluations
Salary information
Disciplinary actions
Any other personnel records maintained by the New York City Department of Education
Any and all communications related to Eric Adams, including but not limited to:
Emails
Text messages
Memos
Letters
Reports
Any other written or electronic communication
As a member of the public, I have a right to access these records to gain a better understanding of the professional conduct and performance of Ms. Collins and any communications related to the Mayor of New York City.

Please be advised that any attempt to withhold, redact, or destroy information related to this request will result in legal action and complaint. The failure to comply with FOIL is a serious matter and can result in both criminal and civil penalties. Therefore, I strongly urge you to comply with this request in a timely and complete manner.

Last, I would like to bring to your attention the case law supporting my request:

New York Times Co. v. U.S. Dep't of Justice, 756 F.3d 100, 117 (2d Cir. 2014) (holding that "the public has a vital interest in information regarding the operations of its government" and that the FOIA "embodies the basic principle that an informed citizenry is essential to democracy").

Matter of John P. v. Whalen, 54 N.Y.2d 89, 96 (1981) (stating that "FOIL expresses this State's strong commitment to open government and public accountability and imposes a broad duty on government to make its records available to the public").

Please note that any attempt to withhold, redact, or destroy information related to this request will result in legal action and complaint.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Good Citizen

communications.subject: RE: New York Freedom of Information Law Request #FOIL-2023-040-00186
communications.communication:
Re: FOIL Request Clarification, Reference Number F21,658

Dear Ms. Schatzle,

I am writing to provide clarification for my FOIL request, specifically pertaining to portions five through six of my request. In order to be more specific in my request, I am seeking the following record types related to personnel records:

Performance evaluations
Disciplinary records
Training records
Attendance records
Any correspondence regarding promotions, demotions, or transfers
Regarding the email request, I understand the need for clarification on the different types of email recipients. Please find the definitions for each type below:

Sent mail: Emails sent by the subject employee.
CC (Carbon Copy): Emails where the subject employee is included as a secondary recipient, typically for their information or awareness.
BCC (Blind Carbon Copy): Emails where the subject employee is included as a hidden recipient, usually to maintain their privacy or confidentiality.
Metadata: The data providing information about the emails in question, such as sender, recipient(s), date and time, subject line, and email size.
Please ensure that your search for responsive records includes the above-mentioned email types and associated metadata.

As established in the case law Matter of Data Tree, LLC v. Romaine, 9 NY3d 454 (2007), the courts have determined that email metadata, as a component of electronic records, is subject to disclosure under the Freedom of Information Law.


I appreciate your prompt attention to this matter and look forward to receiving your response. If you have any questions or require further clarification, please do not hesitate to contact me 

Sincerely

Jordan

communications.subject: RE: Georgia Open Records Act Request #PD-1146-2023
communications.communication:
Thank you.

The Georgia Information Sharing and Analysis Center is "a multi-agency task force managed and supervised by the GBI.  GISAC works in cooperation with the Georgia Office of Homeland Security on all issues involving threats of terrorism.  By design, GISAC is co-located with the Federal Bureau of Investigation to enhance information sharing." 

The Georgia Information Sharing and Analysis Center readily partners with other law enforcement agencies to share information and data: "In addition to the GBI and the Georgia Office of Homeland Security, GISAC partners include the Georgia State Patrol, Georgia Department of Corrections, Georgia Association Chiefs of Police, Georgia Sheriff’s Association, Georgia Fire Chief’s Association, Georgia Department of Public Health, and the Georgia Technology Authority.  Federal partners include the Federal Bureau of Investigation, US Department of Homeland Security and U. S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement."

I am requesting documents which detail the agreements to share data and information between the Doraville Police Department and the Georgia Information Sharing and Analysis Center. These agreements could include contracts, MOUs, data sharing agreements, policies, procedures, protocols, or any other documents which describe the agreements and relationships held between the Doraville Police Department and the Georgia Information Sharing and Analysis Center. The agreements may be held with the GBI as the GBI staffs the Georgia Information Sharing and Analysis Center.

communications.subject: Re: [External Sender] RE: Georgia Open Records Act Request #PD-1146-2023
communications.communication: Thank you for clarifying. I will send back to the Police Department for processing. Thank you.

 Our Police Department has researched this to include a search of PD records, inquiries with PD staff, and a call with GBI. We do not have any responsive records to this request regarding contracts, MOUs, etc. We have one PD policy that references GISAC, and it is attached here as the only responsive record we hold for this Open Records Request. 
  
 Respectfully, 
  
 Doraville Records

Live Birth Data including constant birth rate, long term, short term and average birth rates for within the district for current and previous 6 years.

Birth to Kindergarten Survival Ratio used for the past 10 years by year.

Projected Kindergarten Enrollment for the past 10 years by year, and supporting data.

Any communications with NYS DOH or County DOH or other data service provider requesting, receiving or inquiring regarding live birth data, birth to kindergarten survival rate or other statistical data used for projecting enrollment.

Copies of all enrollment projections for the past 6 years and source statistical data, including but not limited to live birth data which were used to provide projected enrollment data upon which securities purchasers rely.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jackson Parker

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Hacking Team
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records relating to or mentioning Hacking Team, including communications (i.e. emails, memos, letters, etc.) to or from the organization, contracts, bids and invoices to or from the organization, as well as any records relating to the 2015 hack of the organization, the subsequent release of their files and the republication of their emails on the WikiLeaks website.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Emma Best

communications.subject: Hacking Team FOIA Request
communications.communication:
Hello Ms. Best,

I'm an attorney with the U.S. Secret Service, and your appeal of the FOIA office's decision regarding your request for records related to The Hacking Team was recently assigned to me. I've review a portion of the records that the agency located in response to your request, and I was hoping we could schedule a quick phone call this week to discuss your appeal. I have a general sense of the email records that we have that mention The Hacking Team, and I'd be happy to describe what I've reviewed so far and hopefully determine which of these records would be useful to you and which would not. That way I could provide you with a smaller quantity of potentially useful records in a shorter period of time.

I should be free any time Wednesday morning, Thursday, or Friday.

Best,
Steve Giballa
Senior Counsel, Cyber Law
United States Secret Service
202-507-1494

communications.communication:

Emma

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request: Hacking Team
communications.communication:
Hi Emma,

No problem  - I can describe at least the primary question that will help define the set of records that you’re requesting. Our CIO’s search of USSS email records turned up a bit over 30,000 emails that included the phrase “Hacking Team.” From the couple thousand I’ve reviewed so far, most of these are emails from the Hacking Team that appear to have been distributed to a kind of list-serve. Each email is typically a link to a news story about either cybercrime or just a foreign policy/national security story, with some editorializing from David Vincenzetti. We have multiple copies of each of these emails, which appear to have been sent to the list on a daily basis.

So I think the initial question is are you interested in receiving copies of these emails from the Hacking Team? Or would you rather only receive records of emails generated within the USSS that are in some way about the Hacking Team? That second category is going to be much smaller.

I’m happy to answer any follow-up questions about this as well. Hope the recovery is going well.
-Steve

title: Purchase records and 'less lethal' use records (Humboldt County Sheriff's Office)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Purchase records and 'less lethal' use records (Humboldt County Sheriff's Office)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. Purchase records, invoices, procurement documents and other documents sufficient to show any and all disbursement of public funds for the acquisition by your agency since July 1, 2015 of any of the following:
• Firearms of .50 caliber or greater
• Patrol rifles (as commonly denominated for law enforcement use) or assault rifles (as defined in Sections 30510 and 30515 of the California Penal Code)
• Wheeled vehicles that are built or modified to provide ballistic protection to their occupants, such as Bearcats or armored personnel carriers.
• Projectile launch platforms, such as 40mm projectile launchers, "bean bag" or specialty impact munition ("SIM") weapons, and "riot guns" used to disperse chemical agents
• Long-Range Acoustic Device (LRAD)

2. Purchase records, invoices, procurement documents and other documents sufficient to show any and all disbursement of public funds for the acquisition by your agency since July 1, 2018 of explosives and pyrotechnics, such as "flash bang" grenades and explosive breaching tools, and chemical weapons such as "teargas" and "pepper balls".

3. Records of deployment by your agency since January 1, 2020 of projectile launch platforms, such as 40mm projectile launchers, "bean bag" or specialty impact munition ("SIM") weapons, and "riot guns" used to disperse chemical agents; explosives and pyrotechnics, such as "flashbang" grenades and explosive breaching tools; and chemical weapons such as "teargas" and "pepper balls".

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.
In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

If you would like to discuss this request, please feel free to reach out to me, John Lindsay-Poland, American Friends Service Committee, at 510-282-8983.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

John Lindsay-Poland

Stuart Martin

title: Count of City of Chicago employees by Ward and department

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: Count of City of Chicago employees by Ward and department
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

A count by Ward of home address of all City of Chicago employees (sworn and non-sworn for CPD) by department of employment for the years 2010, 2015, and 2019 (three years, separately). They could have been employed anytime in the year; it does not need to be continuous.

Specifically, for each year, please provide a spreadsheet including data under the following fields (count of employees is grouped by Ward, year, and department):

Ward

Year

Department

Employee_count

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.


Sincerely,

Sandra Tilmon

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Sandra Tilmon

communications.subject: Georgia Open Records Act Request: GORA Request: Fusus
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All contracts, licenses, MOUs, MOAs, data agreements, letters of intent, State of Work documents, Scope of Work documents, and other agreement documents with Fusus.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

e

In reference to providing the names of locations we have Fusus agreements with, we cannot disclose that information due to the following exemption from the Georgia Records Act. 

Records that reveal the names, home addresses, telephone numbers, security codes, e-mail addresses, or any other data or information developed, collected, or received by counties or municipalities in connection with neighborhood watch or public safety notification programs or with the installation, servicing, maintaining, operating, selling, or leasing of burglar alarm systems, fire alarm systems, or other electronic security systems;

communications.subject: Ohio Open Records Law Request: Open Records Request: Ohio Violent Crime Reduction Grant
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

According to a press release from Gov. Mike DeWine's office, the Cleveland Heights Police Department received a grant of $658,197.17 as part of the Ohio Violent Crime Reduction Grant program: https://content.govdelivery.com/attachments/OHIOGOVERNOR/2023/02/22/file_attachments/2416264/Violent%20Crime%20Reduction%20Program%20Grant%20Summaries%20through%20R12.pdf

Pursuant to the Ohio Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of all documents, including but not limited to, applications, agreements, and reporting documents for the Cleveland Heights Police Department's $658,197.17 grant as part of the Ohio Violent Crime Reduction Grant program described in the press release linked above.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

e

communications.subject: Tennessee Public Records Act Request: Child care licensing records 2019-present (Department of Human Services)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Tennessee Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Historical licensing data for all licensed child care providers (active and closed) that were open anytime from 1/1/19-present:
•	Provider name or ID
•	Provider address
•	Latest license issue date and expiration date 
•	First license issue date
•	Any additional provider data that your agency collects

If electronic records from before 1/1/19 are available, I’d be happy to collect them as well.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Kent Hoover, a citizen of Tennessee, in coordination with Gabrielle Pepin.

title: AIDS Healthcare Foundation Elevator at Madison Hotel (Los Angeles Department of Building and Safety)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: AIDS Healthcare Foundation Elevator at Madison Hotel (Los Angeles Department of Building and Safety)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All documents from ONLY January 1, 2023 to the present concerning the elevator at the Madison Hotel, located at 423 E. 7th Street, Los Angeles, CA 90014 (the "elevator"). Please note this ONLY asks for documents dated February 1, 2023 to the present, and ONLY about the elevator. This includes any of the following:
1. Applications for permits, and/or permits for any work or repairs on the elevator.
2. Orders to Comply
3. Inspection Reports
4. Emails or texts concerning the elevator to or from any of the following individuals: Robert Galardi (Housing Dept.), Tony Rosales (Housing Dept) , David Jennings (DBS), Darla Abel (DBS),  Jesse Leyva (DBS), Adam Burgess (DBS),  Brett Christensen (DBS), Ben Perez (DBS), Graciela Cota (DBS). 
5. Any complaints made by any member of the public about the elevator.
6. Photos or videos of the elevator
7. Incident reports about the elevator
8. Applications for plan checks and/or approvals/or notices of corrections needed about the elevator

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Annette Morasch

I also saw in the HCID records that the DBS inspector had taken photographs of the elevator.  For instance, this 2x4, or 4x4 underneath the carriage splintered. I'm sure the DBS inspectors would have noted this, and would have noted the bolt holding the wood together.

I see applications for plan checks, but no applications for permits. So there is not a way that I can see what the applicant intended on doing to the elevator.

Please supplement the production. Thank you.

title: MO Dept of Public Safety Employment/Compensation Data

communications.subject: The Missouri Sunshine Law Request: MO Dept of Public Safety Employment/Compensation Data

communications.communication: Please see the attached response.

communications.subject: RE: The Missouri Sunshine Law Request: MO Dept of Public Safety Employment/Compensation Data
communications.communication:
Hi Judy, 

After reviewing the statute, I understand that I requested information that is not open to the Sunshine request.  If allowed, I would like to revise my request to list only available documents with employee name, position, salary and hire date for fiscal years of both 2022 and 2023.  Also, I am requesting fees pleased be waived if at all possible. Or please notify me of any fees before fulfilling the request. 

Thank you.

I understand you wish to revise your request to now seek the following: employee name, position, salary and hire date for FY22 and FY23. The original estimate that the request will be processed in fifteen days continues to be the estimated length of time necessary to fulfill this updated request.  Thank you.

Attached is a spreadsheet containing those records sought in your records request. The below-provided definitions explains each employee class listed on the attached spreadsheet:
-           PUS = designates exception based paid employees. Exception based employees are those paid salary listed unless we tell the system changes are necessary. An example would be using a leave without pay code
-           HRLY = designates positive paid employees. These employees are paid hourly, and these hours must be entered into our system.

This fulfills and concludes this record request.

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Public Records Request - AdventHealth
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, s. 286.011, F.S., I hereby request the following records:

All records related to AdventHealth also known as Adventist Health System from 2019 to 2023 (to the date of the day of processing) with respect to contracts and legal documents and within your agency's possession, the City of Altamonte Springs. More specifically, I request contracts and other legal documents that are in effect during the time frame specified.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering and not for commercial usage.

In the event that fees cannot be waived, I grant permission for fees up to $30. If the fees are still in excess of $30, please let me know as well as the number of results produced and I will further revise the criteria. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

If you deny any part of this request, please cite each specific exemption you think justifies your refusal to release the information and notify me of appeal procedures available under the law.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Bailey Pillon

title: Ayer Gage Cannabis Correspondence (Ayer Police Department)

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Ayer Gage Cannabis Correspondence (Ayer Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Massachusetts Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

Please provide any municipal and/or Ayer law enforcement communications—internal, external, email, or otherwise—that mention "Gage", "Gage Cannabis", and/or any kind of correspondence related to an "I love the 90's" planned for Red Tail Golf Club at 15 Bulge Road, Devens on Friday, September 22, 2023. Please search back to June 1, 2023.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest, as suggested but not stipulated by the recommendations of the Massachusetts Supervisor of Public Records. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, and is not made for commercial usage.

I expect the request to be filled in an accessible format, including for screen readers, which provide text-to-speech for persons unable to read print. Files that are not accessible to screen readers include, for example, .pdf image files as well as physical documents.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Chris Faraone

Dear Miriam: 

RE: Chicago Public Schools FOIA Request N014147-090423 
Thank you again for using the Chicago Public Schools FOIA Center. 
Under the Freedom of Information Act, a public body may extend the time to respond to a FOIA request by up to 5 business days for a limited number of reasons. 5 ILCS 140/3(e). 
We are extending the time to respond to your request by 5 business days for one or more of the following reason(s): 
(  ) the requested records are stored in whole or in part at other locations than the office having charge of the requested records; 
( )  the request requires the collection of a substantial number of specified records; 
( ) the request is couched in categorical terms and requires an extensive search for the records responsive to it; 
( ) the requested records have not been located in the course of routine search and additional efforts are being made to locate them; 
(  ) the requested records require examination and evaluation by personnel having the necessary competence and discretion to determine if they are exempt from disclosure under Section 7 of this Act or should be revealed only with appropriate deletions; 
(x) the request for records cannot be complied with by the public body within the time limits prescribed by 5 ILCS 140/3 (c) without unduly burdening or interfering with the operations of the public body; 
( ) there is need for consultation, which shall be conducted with all practicable speed, with another public body or among two or more components of a public body having a substantial interest in the determination or in the subject matter of the request 
Sincerely, 

Annie Righi 
FOIA Officer 
Chicago Public Schools

October 4, 2023 Miriam Bhimani 151572-21668578@requests.muckrock.com 
RE: Chicago Public Schools FOIA Request N014147-090423 
Dear Ms. Bhimani: This letter is in reply to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request seeking the following information: Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records: 

Supply the Investigative Memoranda with the following File Numbers: 

Investigative Memorandum #7815 
Investigative Memorandum #7816 
Investigative Memorandum #7817 
Investigative Memorandum #7818 
Investigative Memorandum #7819 
Investigative Memorandum #7820 
Investigative Memorandum #7821 
Investigative Memorandum #7822 
Investigative Memorandum #7823 
Investigative Memorandum #7824 RESPONSE : Documents responsive to your request are available to download via the CPS FOIA Center at www.cps.edu/FOIARequests . Please log in with your username and password to access the records. Under the rules of FOIA, private information and unique identifiers contained within public records are exempt from public disclosure; those portions have been redacted including date of birth, employee identification numbers, personal phone numbers, home addresses, and other highly personal information. Pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7 (1)(b), “Private information, unless disclosure is required by another provision of this Act, a State or federal law or a court order,” and pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(c), “Personal information contained within public records, the disclosure of which would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy, unless the disclosure is consented to in writing by the individual subjects of the information. “Unwarranted invasion of personal privacy” means the disclosure of information that is highly personal or objectionable to a reasonable person and in which the subject’s right to privacy outweighs the legitimate public interest in obtaining the information. The disclosure of information that bears on the public duties of public employees and officials shall not be considered an invasion of personal privacy. Certain redactions have been made pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(a) and the corresponding 105 ILCS 5/34-18.5(b) which prohibits the release of background check information. Personally identifiable student record information has been redacted in accordance with the Illinois School Student Records Act 105 ILCS 10/1 et seq. and the corresponding Section 7.5(r) FOIA exemption (5 ILCS 140/7.5(r)). Furthermore, redactions have been applied pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(a) which exempts from release “[i]nformation specifically prohibited from disclosure by federal or State law” and the corresponding s ection 11 of the Abused and Neglected Child Reporting Act which provides that “[a]ll records concerning reports of child abuse and neglect or records concerning referrals under this Act and all records generated as a result of such reports or referrals, shall be confidential and shall not be disclosed except as specifically authorized by this Act or other applicable law.” 325 ILCS 5/11. To the extent you consider this a denial, pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a) you may file a Request for Review with the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at: Public Access Counselor; Office of the Attorney General; 500 South 2nd Street; Springfield, IL 62706.  You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court; 5 ILCS 140/11. If you have any questions, please contact our office at (773) 553-3500. Thank you for your request. Sincerely, Annie Righi Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Mark Keith Robinson service records
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All military service records for Mark Keith Robinson, DOB:  August 18, 1968, including but not limited to discharge paperwork, training logs, and service awards.

I would ask that all documents be released on a rolling basis as they become available. 

If you choose to deny this request, please provide a written explanation for the denial including a reference to the specific statutory exemption(s) upon which you rely. 

Also, please provide all segregable portions of otherwise exempt material.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Albert Serna Jr.

communications.subject: Fwd: Freedom of Information Act Request: Mark Keith Robinson service records
communications.communication:
Dear Mr. Serna:

Thank you for submitting your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to
the National Archives and Records Administration (NARA) via email to
foia@nara.gov. We received your request on September 28, 2023.  Your
request states:

*Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following
records: All military service records for Mark Keith Robinson, DOB: August
18, 1968, including but not limited to discharge paperwork, training logs,
and service awards.*

Due to the nature of your inquiry, we are forwarding your request by this
email to the National Personnel Records Center (NPRC) for Military Records
in St. Louis for appropriate handling.  The NPRC will assign your request a
tracking number and respond directly to you.  In the future, if you need to
contact the NPRC, you can do so by mail or fax to the following address:

National Personnel Records Center
1 Archives Drive
St. Louis, Missouri 63138

Telephone:   314-801-0800
Telephone (Toll Free):  1-866-272-6272 (only within the US)
Fax:  314-801-9195

For your reference, below you will find your original submission.

On our website at https://www.archives.gov/veterans/military-service-records
you can find information about requesting Official Military Personnel Files
(OMPFs) that are not yet archival records fully open to the public.  At the
website for the National Archives at St. Louis,
https://www.archives.gov/st-louis/ <https://www.archives.gov/st-louis/%20>,
you will find information about requesting Official Military Personnel
Files that are now archival records open to the public.  The OMPF normally
becomes an archival record 62 years after the date of discharge.

At www.archives.gov/foia <http://www.archives.gov/foia%20> we provide
information about FOIA.  On our home page, www.archives.gov, you can learn
about the resources that we offer to the public, and access our online
catalog.

Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, and pursuant to guidance received from the
Office of Management and Budget (OMB), NARA had adjusted its normal
operations to balance the need of completing its mission-critical work
while also adhering to the recommended social distancing for the safety of
our staff.  NPRC is working with a reduced on site staff who are
prioritizing veterans' burial requests, homeless veterans, and medical
emergency requests.  As a result of this re-prioritization of activities,
you may experience a delay in receiving a substantive response to your FOIA
request.  We apologize for this inconvenience and appreciate your
understanding and patience.

Sincerely,
Ashley Bryan
Government Information Specialist
Office of General Counsel (NGC)
National Archives and Records Administration
8601 Adelphi Road
College Park, Maryland, 20740-6001
301-837-3642

title: Pride Month 2017, 2018, 2019 (National Archives and Records Administration)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Pride Month 2017, 2018, 2019 (National Archives and Records Administration)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Copies of records mentioning or describing Pride Month activities, events or observances in 2017, 2018 or 2019. This includes, but is not limited to:

* directives
* policies
* pride flag
* commemoration
* publications
* emails, memos, letters, and other communications with OGAs or the White House

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Emma Best
